{"title_page": "L\u00f6ve (game engine)", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name = L\u00d6VE\n| released = {{Start date and age|2008|01|13}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://love2d.org/wiki/Version_History |title=L\u00d6VE version history |accessdate=2019-06-01 }}</ref>\n| latest release version = 11.3<ref>{{cite web |url=https://love2d.org/wiki/11.3 |title=L\u00d6VE 11.3 |accessdate=2020-03-26 }}</ref>\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|27}}\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| platform = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br />[[Linux]]<br> [[Mac OS X]]<br> [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], other\n| genre = [[Game engine]]\n| license = [[zlib license]]\n| website = {{URL|https://love2d.org/}}\n}}\n'''L\u00d6VE''' (or Love2D) is an [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Cross-platform software|cross-platform]] [[Game engine|engine]] for developing 2D [[Video game|computer games]]. Designed in [[C++]], it uses [[Lua (programming language)|Lua]] as a [[programming language]]. It is published under the [[zlib license|zlib license]].\n\nThe API provided by the engine gives access to the video and sound functions of the host machine through the [[Library (computing)|libraries]] [[Simple DirectMedia Layer|SDL]] and [[OpenGL]], or since version 0.10 also [[OpenGL ES]] 2 and 3.<ref name=\"0.10.0\">https://love2d.org/wiki/0.10.0</ref> Fonts can be rendered by the [[FreeType]] engine.<ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=http://korben.info/love-framework.html| title=The power of L\u00f6ve !| author=Korben|date=January 14, 2011| website=Korben.info}}</ref> A version of the engine called piL\u00f6ve has been specifically ported to [[Raspberry Pi]].<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://pilove.mitako.eu/| title=PiLove - L\u00d6VE on RaspberryPI| website=mitako.eu}}</ref>\n\nIt also provides a basic \"sandbox\" management of the [[Computer file|files]] in order to avoid giving access to all its disk to the executed games.\n\nL\u00f6ve is still maintained by its original [[Software developer|developers]].\n\nThis engine is frequently found in the compositions of video game development [[competition]]s, such as the international competition [[Ludum Dare]].<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://ludumdare.com/compo/tag/love2d/|title=Posts Tagged'love2d'|website=[[Ludum Dare]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, it was the 10th game engine most used by independents on the site [[itch.io]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://boingboing.net/2018/07/17/the-most-popular-engines-for-i.html| title=The most popular engines for indie games| author=Rob Beschizza| date= July 17, 2018| website=Boingboing}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Version\n!Code name\n!Added\n!Release date\n|-\n|0.1.1\n|Santa-Power\n|\n* Reading and displaying images\n* Reading and playing sounds\n* Load and use fonts\n*\n|January 13, 2008\n|-\n|0.2.0\n|Mini-Moose\n|\n* Added a screen that displays if no game is loaded\n* Adding an animation system\n*\n|February 6, 2008\n|-\n|0.2.1\n|Impending Doom\n|\n*\n*\n|March 29, 2008\n|-\n|0.3.0\n|Mutant Vermin\n|\n* Addition of the particle system\n|June 2008\n|-\n|0.3.1\n|Meat Space\n|\n*\n|June 2008\n|-\n|0.3.2\n|Lemony Fresh\n|\n*\n|August 29, 2008\n|-\n|0.4.0\n|Taco Beam\n|\n* Added [[Physics engine]] [[Box2D]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|author=Florent Zara|title=L\u00f6ve Output 0.4.0 free game engine, 2D|url=https://linuxfr.org/news/sortie-de-l%C3%B6ve-040-engine-free-play-2d|website=[[Linux]]|date= September 1, 2008}}</ref>\n|July 4, 2008\n|-\n|0.5.0\n|Salted Nuts\n|\n* Joystick support\n*Support of protocols [[TCP Port Service Multiplexer|TCP]]/UDP using luasocket\n*\n|January 2, 2009\n|-\n|0.6.0\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n* Removes the animation system\n*\n|December 24, 2009\n|-\n|0.6.1\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n*\n|February 7, 2010\n|-\n|0.6.2\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n*\n|March 6, 2010\n|-\n|0.7.0\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|December 5, 2010\n|-\n|0.7.1\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2011\n|-\n|0.7.2\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|May 5, 2011\n|-\n|0.8.0\n|Rubber Piggy\n|\n*\n|April 2, 2012\n|-\n|0.9.0\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|December 13, 2013\n|-\n|0.9.1\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|April 1, 2014\n|-\n|0.9.2\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2015\n|-\n|0.10.0\n|Super Toast\n|\n* Supports [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|language=en|author=Christian Nutt|title=New version of free L\u00d6VE 2D game framework adds mobile support|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/262568/New_version_of_free_LVE_2D_game_framework_adds_mobile_support.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|date = December 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|December 22, 2015\n|-\n|0.10.1\n|Super Toast\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2016\n|-\n|0.10.2\n|Super Toast\n|\n*\n|October 31, 2016\n|-\n|11.0\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|April 1, 2018\n|-\n|11.1\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|April 15, 2018\n|-\n|11.2\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|November 25, 2018\n|-\n|11.3\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|October 27, 2019\n|}\n\nLutro is a lua game framework for [[RetroArch|libretro]], partial port of the L\u00d6VE<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=https://github.com/libretro/libretro-lutro|title=Lutro|website=github}}</ref> API. ChaiLove follows a similar path by offering an implementation in [[ChaiScript]], an embedded and cross-platform scripting language for [[C++]] (C++14).<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=https://www.libretro.com/index.php/chailove/ |title=ChaiLove - Another Take on 2D Game Development| date= December 26, 2017| author=RobLoach| website=libretro}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nThese features come with the game engine:\n* support of Open GL pixel shaders [[OpenGL Shading Language|GLSL]],\n* touchscreen support,\n* support for [[UTF-8]],\n* supports image formats [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]], [[JPEG]], [[GIF]], [[Truevision TGA|TGA]] and [[BMP file format|BMP]],<ref>{{Cite web| language=en| url=http://linux.softpedia.com/get/GAMES-ENTERTAINMENT/Arcade/LOVE-34309.shtml| title=An Open Source and cross-platform 2D game engine that provides dynamic gaming experiences| website=[[Softpedia]]| author=Marius Nestor}}</ref>\n* possibility to use the [[physics engine]] in 2D [[Box2D]] (can be disabled, to lighten the library),\n* luasocket library for network communications [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]/[[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]],\n* lua-enet library, another network library implementing Enet, a reliable protocol based on UDP\n* native management of tiles created by the Tiled.<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://lua.space/gamedev/using-tiled-maps-in-love| title=Using Tiled Maps in L\u00d6VE| author=Landon Manning|date= December 21, 2015| website=lua.space}}</ref>\n\n== Portability and Usage ==\nL\u00f6ve is based on a language and libraries that aim to be cross-platform. L\u00f6ve is therefore cross-platform.\n\nApplication compatibility is not ensured between different L\u00f6ve versions.\n\n== Additional libraries ==\nThere are various libraries to improve basic functions, such as object programming with [[Inheritance (object-oriented programming)|Inheritance]]  and overload, interpolations, camera management, network multiplayer management, game state management, configuration etc.\n\nThe Simple Tiled Implementation library allows users to load levels as tiles, edit using Tiled<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://www.mapeditor.org/|title=Tiled|website=mapeditor.org}}</ref> and display them in games. It works in conjunction with [[Box2D]] for collision management with this decor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/karai17/Simple-Tiled-Implementation|title=Simple Tiled Implementation|website=github.com}}</ref>\n\nThe anim8 library allows users to load animations, for characters for example, from an image grid into a bitmap file ([[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] or [[JPEG]]).<ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=https://love2d.org/wiki/anim8|title=Anim8|website=love2d.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=https://github.com/kikito/anim8| title=An animation library for L\u00d6VE|website=github}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a free platform ([[GNU General Public License|GPLv3]]) called LIKO-12, inspired by the PICO-8 ''fantasy console'' and using L\u00d6VE, allowing to develop applications in a limited resolution, backup/restore in the modified PNG format, in the same way as the [[video game cartridge]]s of the [[game console]]s or some of the first [[microcomputer]]s, and export them to [[HTML5]] or to systems supported by L\u00d6VE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?f=5&t=82913| title=[LIKO-12 V0.0.5 PRE] An open-source pico-8-inspired game dev environment for love2d| website=love2d.org|date= September 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book|language=en|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=beL7AAAAAAQBAJ |title=L\u00d6VE2d for Lua Game Programming -master the Lua programming language and build exciting strategy-based games in 2D using the L\u00d6VE framework| author=Damilare Darmie Akinlaja|publisher=PacktPub| date=2013| oclc=864886612| isbn=9781461946038}}\n* {{Cite book|language=en|author=Jayant Varma| title=Learn Lua for iOS game development| publisher=Apress|date=2012| oclc=834071764| isbn=9781430246633}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://love2d.org/}}\n* {{cite web|title=Love repo|url=https://github.com/love2d/love|website= on [[GitHub]]|language=en|publication-date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=Your First Love2d Game in 200 Lines - Part 1 of 3|url=http://www.osmstudios.com/tutorials/your-first-love2d-game-in-200-lines-part-1-of-3|website=osmstudios|publication-date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=How to Learn L\u00d6VE (Love2D)|url=https://gamedevelopment.tutsplus.com/articles/how-to-learn-love-love2d--gamedev-4331|author=Agam More|website=[[Envato|Envato Tuts+]]}}\n\n\n{{Portal|Video games|Computer programming|Free and open-source software}}\n\n{{Video game engines|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Love}}\n[[Category:Video game engines]]\n[[Category:Free game engines]]\n[[Category:Lua-scriptable game engines]]\n[[Category:Software using the zlib license]]\n[[Category:2008 software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name = L\u00d6VE\n| released = {{Start date and age|2008|01|13}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://love2d.org/wiki/Version_History |title=L\u00d6VE version history |accessdate=2019-06-01 }}</ref>\n| latest release version = 11.3<ref>{{cite web |url=https://love2d.org/wiki/11.3 |title=L\u00d6VE 11.3 |accessdate=2020-03-26 }}</ref>\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2019|10|27}}\n| programming language = [[C++]]\n| platform = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br />[[Linux]]<br> [[Mac OS X]]<br> [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], other\n| genre = [[Game engine]]\n| license = [[zlib license]]\n| website = {{URL|https://love2d.org/}}\n}}\n'''L\u00d6VE''' (or Love2D) is an [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Cross-platform software|cross-platform]] [[Game engine|engine]] for developing 2D [[Video game|computer games]]. Designed in [[C++]], it uses [[Lua (programming language)|Lua]] as a [[programming language]]. It is published under the [[zlib license|zlib license]].\n\nThe API provided by the engine gives access to the video and sound functions of the host machine through the [[Library (computing)|libraries]] [[Simple DirectMedia Layer|SDL]] and [[OpenGL]], or since version 0.10 also [[OpenGL ES]] 2 and 3.<ref name=\"0.10.0\">https://love2d.org/wiki/0.10.0</ref> Fonts can be rendered by the [[FreeType]] engine.<ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=http://korben.info/love-framework.html| title=The power of L\u00f6ve !| author=[[Korben]]|date=January 14, 2011| website=Korben.info}}</ref> A version of the engine called piL\u00f6ve has been specifically ported to [[Raspberry Pi]].<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://pilove.mitako.eu/| title=PiLove - L\u00d6VE on RaspberryPI| website=mitako.eu}}</ref>\n\nIt also provides a basic \"sandbox\" management of the [[Computer file|files]] in order to avoid giving access to all its disk to the executed games.\n\nL\u00f6ve is still maintained by its original [[Software developer|developers]].\n\nThis engine is frequently found in the compositions of video game development [[competition]]s, such as the international competition [[Ludum Dare]].<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://ludumdare.com/compo/tag/love2d/|title=Posts Tagged'love2d'|website=[[Ludum Dare]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, it was the 10th game engine most used by independents on the site [[itch.io]].<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://boingboing.net/2018/07/17/the-most-popular-engines-for-i.html| title=The most popular engines for indie games| author=Rob Beschizza| date= July 17, 2018| website=Boingboing}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Version\n!Code name\n!Added\n!Release date\n|-\n|0.1.1\n|Santa-Power\n|\n* Reading and displaying images\n* Reading and playing sounds\n* Load and use fonts\n*\n|January 13, 2008\n|-\n|0.2.0\n|Mini-Moose\n|\n* Added a screen that displays if no game is loaded\n* Adding an animation system\n*\n|February 6, 2008\n|-\n|0.2.1\n|Impending Doom\n|\n*\n*\n|March 29, 2008\n|-\n|0.3.0\n|Mutant Vermin\n|\n* Addition of the particle system\n|June 2008\n|-\n|0.3.1\n|Meat Space\n|\n*\n|June 2008\n|-\n|0.3.2\n|Lemony Fresh\n|\n*\n|August 29, 2008\n|-\n|0.4.0\n|Taco Beam\n|\n* Added [[Physics engine]] [[Box2D]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|author=Florent Zara|title=L\u00f6ve Output 0.4.0 free game engine, 2D|url=https://linuxfr.org/news/sortie-de-l%C3%B6ve-040-engine-free-play-2d|website=[[Linux]]|date= September 1, 2008}}</ref>\n|July 4, 2008\n|-\n|0.5.0\n|Salted Nuts\n|\n* Joystick support\n*Support of protocols [[TCP Port Service Multiplexer|TCP]]/UDP using luasocket\n*\n|January 2, 2009\n|-\n|0.6.0\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n* Removes the animation system\n*\n|December 24, 2009\n|-\n|0.6.1\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n*\n|February 7, 2010\n|-\n|0.6.2\n|Jiggly Juice\n|\n*\n|March 6, 2010\n|-\n|0.7.0\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|December 5, 2010\n|-\n|0.7.1\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2011\n|-\n|0.7.2\n|Slavic Game\n|\n*\n|May 5, 2011\n|-\n|0.8.0\n|Rubber Piggy\n|\n*\n|April 2, 2012\n|-\n|0.9.0\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|December 13, 2013\n|-\n|0.9.1\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|April 1, 2014\n|-\n|0.9.2\n|Baby Inspector\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2015\n|-\n|0.10.0\n|Super Toast\n|\n* Supports [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS (Apple)|iOS]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|language=en|author=Christian Nutt|title=New version of free L\u00d6VE 2D game framework adds mobile support|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/262568/New_version_of_free_LVE_2D_game_framework_adds_mobile_support.php|website=[[Gamasutra]]|date = December 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|December 22, 2015\n|-\n|0.10.1\n|Super Toast\n|\n*\n|February 14, 2016\n|-\n|0.10.2\n|Super Toast\n|\n*\n|October 31, 2016\n|-\n|11.0\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|April 1, 2018\n|-\n|11.1\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|April 15, 2018\n|-\n|11.2\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|November 25, 2018\n|-\n|11.3\n|Mysterious Mysteries\n|\n*\n|October 27, 2019\n|}\n\nLutro is a lua game framework for [[RetroArch|libretro]], partial port of the L\u00d6VE<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=https://github.com/libretro/libretro-lutro|title=Lutro|website=github}}</ref> API. ChaiLove follows a similar path by offering an implementation in [[ChaiScript]], an embedded and cross-platform scripting language for [[C++]] (C++14).<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=https://www.libretro.com/index.php/chailove/ |title=ChaiLove - Another Take on 2D Game Development| date= December 26, 2017| author=RobLoach| website=libretro}}</ref>\n\n== Features ==\nThese features come with the game engine:\n* support of Open GL pixel shaders [[OpenGL Shading Language|GLSL]],\n* touchscreen support,\n* support for [[UTF-8]],\n* supports image formats [[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]], [[JPEG]], [[GIF]], [[Truevision TGA|TGA]] and [[BMP file format|BMP]],<ref>{{Cite web| language=en| url=http://linux.softpedia.com/get/GAMES-ENTERTAINMENT/Arcade/LOVE-34309.shtml| title=An Open Source and cross-platform 2D game engine that provides dynamic gaming experiences| website=[[Softpedia]]| author=Marius Nestor}}</ref>\n* possibility to use the [[physics engine]] in 2D [[Box2D]] (can be disabled, to lighten the library),\n* luasocket library for network communications [[Transmission Control Protocol|TCP]]/[[User Datagram Protocol|UDP]],\n* lua-enet library, another network library implementing Enet, a reliable protocol based on UDP\n* native management of tiles created by the Tiled.<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://lua.space/gamedev/using-tiled-maps-in-love| title=Using Tiled Maps in L\u00d6VE| author=Landon Manning|date= December 21, 2015| website=lua.space}}</ref>\n\n== Portability and Usage ==\nL\u00f6ve is based on a language and libraries that aim to be cross-platform. L\u00f6ve is therefore cross-platform.\n\nApplication compatibility is not ensured between different L\u00f6ve versions.\n\n== Additional libraries ==\nThere are various libraries to improve basic functions, such as object programming with [[Inheritance (object-oriented programming)|Inheritance]]  and overload, interpolations, camera management, network multiplayer management, game state management, configuration etc.\n\nThe Simple Tiled Implementation library allows users to load levels as tiles, edit using Tiled<ref>{{Cite web|language=en|url=http://www.mapeditor.org/|title=Tiled|website=mapeditor.org}}</ref> and display them in games. It works in conjunction with [[Box2D]] for collision management with this decor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/karai17/Simple-Tiled-Implementation|title=Simple Tiled Implementation|website=github.com}}</ref>\n\nThe anim8 library allows users to load animations, for characters for example, from an image grid into a bitmap file ([[Portable Network Graphics|PNG]] or [[JPEG]]).<ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=https://love2d.org/wiki/anim8|title=Anim8|website=love2d.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|language=en| url=https://github.com/kikito/anim8| title=An animation library for L\u00d6VE|website=github}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a free platform ([[GNU General Public License|GPLv3]]) called LIKO-12, inspired by the PICO-8 ''fantasy console'' and using L\u00d6VE, allowing to develop applications in a limited resolution, backup/restore in the modified PNG format, in the same way as the [[video game cartridge]]s of the [[game console]]s or some of the first [[microcomputer]]s, and export them to [[HTML5]] or to systems supported by L\u00d6VE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://love2d.org/forums/viewtopic.php?f=5&t=82913| title=[LIKO-12 V0.0.5 PRE] An open-source pico-8-inspired game dev environment for love2d| website=love2d.org|date= September 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite book|language=en|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=beL7AAAAAAQBAJ |title=L\u00d6VE2d for Lua Game Programming -master the Lua programming language and build exciting strategy-based games in 2D using the L\u00d6VE framework| author=Damilare Darmie Akinlaja|publisher=PacktPub| date=2013| oclc=864886612| isbn=9781461946038}}\n* {{Cite book|language=en|author=Jayant Varma| title=Learn Lua for iOS game development| publisher=Apress|date=2012| oclc=834071764| isbn=9781430246633}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://love2d.org/}}\n* {{cite web|title=Love repo|url=https://github.com/love2d/love|website= on [[GitHub]]|language=en|publication-date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=Your First Love2d Game in 200 Lines - Part 1 of 3|url=http://www.osmstudios.com/tutorials/your-first-love2d-game-in-200-lines-part-1-of-3|website=osmstudios|publication-date=}}\n* {{cite web|title=How to Learn L\u00d6VE (Love2D)|url=https://gamedevelopment.tutsplus.com/articles/how-to-learn-love-love2d--gamedev-4331|author=Agam More|website=[[Envato|Envato Tuts+]]}}\n\n\n{{Portal|Video games|Computer programming|Free and open-source software}}\n\n{{Vi